summary.title: Danish Legal Manuscript
summary.note: The manuscript contains various legal texts, as well as a short miracle text, a description of the border between Denmark and Sweden, diary entries and some accounts. The vast majority of the manuscript is in Danish, but Latin and also Low German occur.

supportDesc.extent: 205 (1-202 + 3 bis, 52 bis, 90 bis [52 bis and 90 bis have been stitched in later]). 215 160

layout.p: The manuscript is written in long lines throughout with 24 to 34 lines per page. The initials, rubrics and some of the running titles are red. The following leaves are blank: fols 3v, 3 bis, 90 bis v, 96v, 111v, 116, 159, 165v, 166v, 169, 172, 175v, 178r-180v, 183v, 202r.

handNote.p: There are several hands in the manuscript.

origin.p: This manuscript was written in Denmark c. 1500.

provenance.p:
According to Kristian Kålund, the AM-slip on the inner face of the front board is similar to the one found in AM 23 4to. The slip has the following content serving as evidence for the provenance of the manuscript: Istud legisterium est elemosina
Domini Birgeri Achiepiscopi Lun
densis etc. pro usu sedis Lun
densis in Schania. ipso die
Nativitatis Joannis Baptiste
M. d. decimo qvinto. Kålund therefore presumes that this manuscript, as well as AM 23 4to, was donated to the episcopal residence of Lund by Archbishop Birger in 1515.

custEvent.p: The manuscript was photographed in January 1986.
New photographs of the manuscript were taken in 1992.

surrogates.p:
The manuscript was photographed in 1986 and 1992. The following copies are kept at The Arnamagnæan Collection in Copenhagen:
Microfilm (master), Neg. 708, from 21 January 1986.
Microfilm (archive), Pos. 653, from 21 January 1986.
Microfilm (master), Neg. 900, from May 1992.
Microfilm (archive), Pos. 803, from May 1992.
Black and white prints from 26 March 1992.
